# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
It has a greedy approach:
* In order to get the highest number from the given digits, we want to replace the first non-9 digit with a 9. Let's replace it with a 9 then, and if the replaced digit has multiple occurrences, replace all the occurrences as well. That way, we will always guarantee that we will get the highest number.
* Similarly, in order to get the lowest number from the given digits, we want to replace the first non-0 digit with a 0. Let's replace it with a 0 then, and if the replaced digit has multiple occurrences, replace all of the occurrences as well. That way, we will always guarantee that we will get the lowest number.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Convert the number to a string.
2. First, we will start by replacing the digits to 9. We create a loop to get the first non-9 digit.
3. Then we replace all of the occurrences of this digit to 9.
4. If all of the digits are 9, then we can just return the number because this is the highest possible number we can get.
5. We do the exact same thing for the minimum number as well, but insteaf of 9 it is 0.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(log n) -- we loop on the digits of the number.
- Space complexity: O(log n) -- because of strNum.

